Detecting relative value refers to the process of comparing the potential returns of alternative investments. For this class there will be two pactical implementations of two such relative value models which provide information on over-, respectively underpriced bonds. The first one is a simple model based on traditional yield to maturity analysis and the second one demonstrates the slightly more complex JP Morgan discount function model, an approach of term-structure of interest modeling. Both have been tested in practical applications in bond relative value research but they have here been adapted for trading purposes. In particular, the real time data feeds have been generalized to be independent of a particular data provider. To use them in a \'93real world\'94 setting, students would require links to current price and bond data as well as utility macros to maintain the bond baskets analyzed.\
