Historically, the corporate bond market has been the \'93smart money\'94 because it is largely driven by institutional investors rather than retail investors. It tends to be more focused on near-term math than on emotion or long-term projections, and as such tends to front-run the equity market, at least in terms of major transitions. In fixed income there is also a \'93mathematical arms race\'94 where increasingly complex quantitative theories are applied without markedly improving the predictive power of the models. Just because a fancy model is wonderful to behold does not mean we should slavishly use its results without thought of the consequences. As Einstein said, \'93If you are out to describe the truth, leave elegance to the tailor.\'94 It would perhaps be time that research in credit made this requirement a priority for improved models and not a futile chase for the ultimate true model that does not exist. Modeling term structure of credit spreads is a great example where a simple redemption yield based reference curve calibrated frequently can be used to generate a list of cheap, respectively rich bonds. \
